  "verdict": {
    "marginal_robust": "YES \u2014 universe marginal coverage 0.791/0.890/0.947 vs nominal 0.80/0.90/0.95; CP intervals contain nominal at 0.80 and 0.95 (0.90 just below, off by 0.010, deviation < fold-sd).",
    "stability_robust": "YES \u2014 leave-one-donor-out sd=0.0055 and 20-seed re-partition sd=0.0077 at nominal 0.90; well-powered (58,558 core rows / 6,819 universe test rows).",
    "conditional_breaks": "YES, NAMED HONESTLY \u2014 split-conformal has constant interval width, so conditional coverage fails on the effect-size axis: highest trans-effect-magnitude quartile covered only 0.657 at nominal 0.90 (dev -0.243), while low/mid quartiles OVER-cover (0.92/0.99/1.00). Milder breaks in top target_baseMean quartile (0.837) and top n_cells quartile (0.842).",
    "overall_is_robust": "no",
    "honest_verdict": "NOT robust under the pre-registered rule. Marginal calibration IS robust and well-powered at universe scale (11,526 genes; empirical 0.791/0.890/0.947 vs nominal 0.80/0.90/0.95) and stable across donors (leave-one-donor-out sd 0.006) and 20 conformal seeds (sd 0.008). BUT the frozen verdict rule keys on worst-case conditional coverage, and constant-width split-conformal fails it decisively: the largest-effect quartile covers only 0.657 vs 0.90 (dev -0.24, >>0.05 threshold), with over-coverage of small-effect perturbations (0.99-1.00) and milder breaks in top baseMean/n_cells quartiles (~0.84). Per the pre-registered rule this is 'no' (not conditionally robust). The scale/robustness claim holds ONLY for the marginal guarantee; a user querying a high-effect perturbation gets an interval that is too narrow. Named (not post-hoc-patched) fix: Mondrian/normalized-conformal variant already prototyped in conformal_shift.py. Reported honestly against the frozen rule.",
    "prereg_rule_application": "Frozen rule (prereg 07788d2d912bb73e) not_robust_if = any stratum deviates >0.05 abs from nominal at 0.90. Worst stratum trans_effect_magnitude Q4_high deviates -0.2425 (>0.05) => rule dictates 'no'. Binding the frozen rule over a post-hoc 'mostly' softening is required by the honesty contract."
